{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τέρας</b>, τό: <br /> <i>genitive</i> <i>Epic dialect</i> αος (not in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus or 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Ionic dialect</i> εος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.37 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <i>nominative</i> <i>Epic dialect</i> τέραα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.394 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Ionic dialect</i> τέρεα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus [same place], τεράᾰτᾰ 2nd c.AD: Dionysius Periegeta 604, 4th c.AD(?): Quintus Smyrnaeus Epicus 5.43; τέρᾱ 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.1410, but τέρᾰ 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “Theriaca” 186; τέρα (quantity not stated) _Attic dialect_ _accusative_ to Moer. p.369 P.,compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1343 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>genitive</i> <i>Epic dialect</i> τεράων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.229, τερέων 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus 155; _Attic dialect_ τερῶν _accusative_ to Moer.[same place], Thom.Mag. p.348 R.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>dative</i> <i>Epic dialect</i> τεράεσσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.398, +others; later τέρασι LXX.Deu.26.8, +others: the forms τέρατ-ος, -ι, -α, -ων are Hellenistic, Moer. pp.366,369 P., Thom.Mag. p.348 R. (τέρατα LXX.Exo.4.21, +others, τεράτωνLXX.Psa.104(105).27)\">LXX+8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>genitive</i> <i>singular</i> τέρως variant in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 10.26.3: lengthened for the sake of meter τείρεα 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.485 (= “IG” 42(1).129.9), 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 692, 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 3.1362; τείρεσιν “hymnus ad Martem” 7; later τείρεσσι “IG” 14.2461.11 (from Massilia)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:— <b>sign, wonder, marvel, portent</b>, ἡμῖν μὲν τόδ᾽ ἔφηνε τ. Ζεύς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.324 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ᾐτέομεν δὲ θεὸν φῆναι τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.173; τοῖσιν.. θεοὶ τέραα προὔφαινον 12.394; τέρας ἧκε Κρόνου πάϊς 21.415 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; Ζεὺς δ᾽ Ἔριδα προΐαλλε.., πολέμοιοτ. μετὰ χερσὶν ἔχουσαν <b>a sign</b> of coming battle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.4 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; especially of <b>signs</b> in heaven, ἀστέρα ἧκε Κρόνου πάϊς.., ναύτῃσι τ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\". 4.76; ἴρισσιν ἐοικότες, ἅς τε Κρονίων ἐν νέφεϊ στήριξε τ. μερόπων ἀνθρώπων 11.28, compare 17.548 \">Refs</a>]; and with <i>passive</i> Verbs, τ. φανήτω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.101 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—so always when the first syllable is <i>lengthened</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"see above:—also in Prose, ἢν δὲ χειμῶνος βροντὴ γένηται, ὡς τέρας θωμάζεται 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.28, compare 6.98; τ. πέμπειν 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.4.15; ἐφάνη 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.57; ἐπιγίνεταί σφι τέρεα [prev. author] 8.37, compare 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 744, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.73, etc.; frequently in “NT”, σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα NT.Mark.13.22, +others \">NT+8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in concrete sense, <b>monster</b>, Διὸς τ. αἰγιόχοιο, of the [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Gorgon 's head, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.742 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of a serpent, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 12.209, “hymnus ad Apollinem” 302 \">Refs</a>]; δάϊον τ., of Typhoeus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 354 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἀπρόσμαχον τ., of Cerberus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1098 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὔρειον τ., of the Sphinx, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 806 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ταῦρον, ἄγριον τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Hipp.” 1214, compare 1247; ὅλον τ. ὀπτήσας.. βασιλεῖ παρέθηκε κάμηλον 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 172.7 (_anapaest meter_), compare 4th c.BC: Epicrates Comicus 3.13 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; used by Cicero of Caesar, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Attic” 8.9.4. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>monstrous birth, monstrosity</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 393b, 394a, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.111, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Generatione Animalium” 769b30, 773a3, 2nd c.AD: Vettius Valens Astrologus 341.13 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὡς ἔθρεψεν ἔκπαγλον τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 548. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> in colloquial language, τέρας λέγεις καὶ θαυμαστόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Hp.Ma.” 283c, compare “Tht.” 163d; τέρας λέγεις, εἰ.. [prev. author] “Men.” 91d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; 'a marvel' of a cup, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 1.56 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, of incredible statements, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Mus.” p.74 K. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5059","accentedUnicode":"τέρας","shortDef":"wonder, miracle, which is by implication a sign or portent","mediumDef":"wonder, miracle, which is by implication a sign or portent <br /><b>a prodigy, portent,</b> <ref='Act.2.19'>Acts 2:19;</ref> <b>a signal act, wonder, miracle,</b> <